---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const title = 'Privacy — Plnt';
const description = 'Privacy policy for the Plnt project and website. Local-first means no data leaves your machine by default.';
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} path="/privacy">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose" style="max-width: 760px;">
      <span class="eyebrow">privacy</span>
      <h1>Privacy</h1>
      <p class="muted">Last updated: June 15, 2026</p>

      <h2>The short version</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Plnt is local-first. The software runs on your machine, reads files you point it at,
        and writes its state to <code>$PLNT_HOME</code>. <strong>No telemetry. No analytics.
        No account.</strong> Nothing is sent to us, because there is no "us" infrastructure
        to send it to.
      </p>

      <h2>1. The software</h2>
      <p>
        Plnt does not phone home. It does not collect crash reports, usage stats, or any
        identifier. There is no built-in network call to a Plnt-controlled endpoint.
      </p>

      <h3>What happens to your data locally</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Files you let agents read</strong> are read by tools running on your machine.</li>
        <li><strong>The blackboard</strong> (<code>$PLNT_HOME/runs/&lt;id&gt;/events.jsonl</code>) records every tool call, model call, and result. You own these files. Delete them at any time.</li>
        <li><strong>Skill files</strong> live in <code>$PLNT_HOME/skills/</code>. Skills you install from external catalogs are versioned by git so you can audit and revert.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>2. When you use a cloud LLM backend</h2>
      <p>
        If you configure <code>PLNT_DEEP_URL</code> or a cloud API key, Plnt will send the
        prompts and context required for inference to that provider. The provider's privacy
        policy then applies to that data. Plnt does not proxy, intercept, or store these calls
        on any Plnt-controlled server — the request goes from your machine to the provider
        directly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every backend selection is logged in <code>events.jsonl</code> with a <code>"backend"</code>
        field, so you can audit which calls went where with one <code>grep</code>.
      </p>

      <h2>3. This website</h2>
      <p>
        <code>plnt.dev</code> is a static site. No cookies, no analytics scripts, no fingerprinting.
        Your browser fetches HTML, CSS, and a tiny amount of JS — nothing else.
      </p>
      <p>
        Standard server access logs (IP, user-agent, requested path, timestamp) may exist on
        the hosting provider's edge for short periods as part of normal operations and DDoS
        protection. These are not used for tracking or shared with third parties.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Outbound links</h2>
      <p>
        The site links to GitHub and the project repository. Once you click such a link, the
        target site's privacy policy applies.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Children</h2>
      <p>
        Plnt is a developer tool. It is not directed at children under 13 and we do not
        knowingly collect information from them.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Changes</h2>
      <p>
        We will note material changes to this policy at the top of the page.
      </p>

      <hr/>
      <p class="dim">
        Questions? Open an issue on <a href="https://github.com/devdattatalele/plnt/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
